    <title>Combined summary - On mempool policy consistency</title>
    <updated>2023-06-16T02:35:48.399502+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2022-November/021183.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>Bitcoin developers are currently discussing various issues related to the Bitcoin network policies. These discussions have been held on the bitcoin-dev mailing list and cover topics such as transaction relay propagation rules, mempool policies, and potential attacks on joint-funded transactions.One of the discussions examined the impact of nodes adopting a more permissive policy on transaction propagation, while another discussed the use of zero-confirmation transactions and the potential exploitation of 0-conf services through out-bidding. Some users are exploiting 0-conf services through a process called "out-bidding" to retrieve funds they sent in error. While this is not a legitimate use case, it is rational. However, developers and node operators do not have to support every use case that someone might find rational.Another debate is about the benefits of enabling fullrbf on the network. Some argue for maximal RBF, while others express concerns about limitations of transaction relay and issues with incentive compatibility. Suhas Daftuar, a Bitcoin Core developer, expresses opposition to the full Replace-By-Fee (fullrbf) network policy, arguing that it could subvert the use case for v3 transactions and break zeroconf business practices. Instead, he suggests supporting disparate use cases to make everything work better rather than breaking things prematurely because others might do so eventually.The email thread between Peter Todd and Yancy delves into the implications of a "full-rbf" policy for transaction replacement. According to Peter, adding a full-rbf config flag is trivial, but there is no consensus over the mempool, so in certain cases, non-full-rbf nodes will broadcast replacements when they didn't receive the "first" transaction first. The author of one email argues that Core should implement a particular mempool policy and only have options that either make it feasible to scale that policy to different hardware limitations or provide options that users can activate en-masse if it turns out people are doing crazy things in the mempool.Furthermore, the discussion highlights the importance of maintaining decentralization/censorship-resistance, privacy, and efficiency in the Bitcoin network. The email also discusses the potential risks involved in miners subscribing to an overlay network with different rules, which could become a centralization risk.Developers have been discussing the inclusion of Full-RBF in Bitcoin Core 24.0, which would replace the opt-in RBF. While some argue that this option could be removed later to prevent negative impacts on compact blocks, others suggest that it may be better to have a uniform transition to avoid degradation of fast block propagation.Overall, finding a reliable solution to the mempool policy issue is complex and requires input from various stakeholders, including zeroconf businesses, lightning and coinjoin devs, and miners. The hope is to find a solution that keeps most stakeholders happy and allows for efficient design of apps and transactions. The email conversation highlights the challenges of balancing user choice and network security in Bitcoin development.</summary>
